      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my undergrad physics final and im a bit stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick, non-math summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. It is different from classical correlation because in classical systems, the properties are determined beforehand, whereas in quantum mechanics, the properties are undefined until measured.\n\nTo put it simply, if you have two entangled particles, measuring one will immediately tell you the state of the other, even if they are light-years apart. This is not just like two coins that land on the same side because they were flipped together; instead, the coins themselves don't have a definite side until you look at them.\n\nThis spooky connection is often described as \"spooky action at a distance\" by Einstein, and it has been proven by experiments like Bell's theorem tests. While classical correlation is like knowing a pair of gloves are separated, one left and one right, quantum entanglement is more like the gloves not having a left or right side until you open the box.\n\nIn the context of your physics final, remember that entanglement allows for non-local correlations that cannot be explained by any local hidden variable theory. This means the particles share a single quantum state, and measuring one collapses",
      "source": "target",
